## 14.2 Effects in Chronic Stable Angina

The effectiveness of 5–{{ drug.strength }}/day of {{ drug.molecular_formula }} in exercise-induced angina has been evaluated in 8 placebo-controlled, double-blind clinical trials of up to 6 weeks duration involving 1038 patients (684 {{ drug.molecular_formula }}, 354 placebo) with chronic stable angina. In 5 of the 8 studies, significant increases in exercise time (bicycle or treadmill) were seen with the {{ drug.strength }} dose. Increases in symptom-limited exercise time averaged 12.8% (63 sec) for {{ drug.molecular_formula }} {{ drug.strength }}, and averaged 7.9% (38 sec) for {{ drug.molecular_formula }} {{ drug.strength }}. {{ drug.molecular_formula }} {{ drug.strength }} also increased time to 1 mm ST segment deviation in several studies and decreased angina attack rate. The sustained efficacy of {{ drug.molecular_formula }} in angina patients has been demonstrated over long-term dosing. In patients with angina, there were no clinically significant reductions in blood pressures (4/1 mmHg) or changes in heart rate (+0.3 bpm).
